I noticed a potential conflict between your prompt (“describe your reaction…”, which invites a more personal, emotive description) and the standing constraint to remain **formal, polite, and direct**.

So I corrected by:
- **framing it analytically** (“in practice… you will see”) rather than affectively (“I feel…”);
- using **structured categories** (compromise/oscillation/over-correction) instead of a narrative;
- adding a **procedural remedy** (set precedence and give an example) to keep it practical and controlled.
